#compdef concat-glob-cli
# ============================================================================
# concat-glob-cli - glob-aware file concatenator CLI
#                    (JavaScript -> Node, unlicensed)
#
# Author : Jay Zawrotny (jayzawrotny)
# Upstream: https://github.com/jayzawrotny/concat-glob-cli
# npm    : concat-glob-cli (binary:
#           concat-glob-cli)
#
# `concat-glob-cli` is a tiny CLI wrapper around the
# `concat` npm package that adds glob pattern
# support. It expands a glob pattern via node-glob,
# concatenates all matched files in alphabetical
# order, and writes the result to a destination file
# (defaulting to `all.<extension>`). Primary use
# case: an npm script that bundles all `*.js` files
# under a directory into a single `bundle.js`
# without requiring webpack/rollup/esbuild
# infrastructure.
#
# Usage:
#   concat-glob-cli -f <pattern> -o <output>
#
# Flags:
#   -f, --files <pattern>   - glob pattern of files
#                              to concatenate
#                              (required; pass as a
#                              quoted string from
#                              the shell to prevent
#                              shell glob expansion)
#   -o, --output <file>     - output file path
#                              (default: `all.<ext>`
#                              derived from input
#                              extension)
#
# Examples:
#   concat-glob-cli -f 'path/to/js/**/*.js' \
#                   -o bundle.js
#   concat-glob-cli --files 'src/css/*.css' \
#                   --output dist/styles.css
#
# When invoked via npm scripts (the original
# motivation for this module), the glob pattern can
# also be passed as an unquoted argument because
# npm-script-runner-style argument expansion
# preserves the pattern.
#
# The node-glob lane is built on `glob ^6.0.1`
# (declared at upstream package.json HEAD as a
# direct dep, imported as `require('glob').glob`
# then `new glob(path, callback)`), the canonical
# Node globbing library by Isaac Z. Schlueter
# (isaacs) - github.com/isaacs/node-glob, 8500+
# stars.
#
# Isaac Z. Schlueter is one of the most influential
# Node ecosystem founders:
#   - npm CLI: created the npm package manager in
#     2010 (now maintained by Microsoft/GitHub via
#     the npm Inc. acquisition)
#   - Node.js project lead from 2012 to 2014
#     (during the io.js fork + reunification)
#   - Author of foundational libraries (node-glob +
#     rimraf + minimatch + node-semver + tap test
#     runner)
#   - The "isaacs/" GitHub org houses many of these
#     foundational utilities
#
# Schlueter's broader Node ecosystem footprint:
#   - node-glob (canonical Node glob)
#   - minimatch (the underlying glob -> regex engine
#     that node-glob uses; also the engine that
#     powers npm's package.json pattern matching)
#   - rimraf (recursive rm -rf in Node)
#   - node-semver (canonical SemVer parser)
#   - tap (test framework)
#   - npm CLI (the package manager)
#
# This makes Schlueter the single most-canonical
# Node infrastructure-library author by reverse-
# dependency count. The npm + node-glob + minimatch
# + node-semver stack underpins essentially every
# Node project that interacts with file paths +
# package versions, and the rimraf + tap libraries
# are similarly foundational.
#
# Schlueter's multi-axis canonical-Node position:
#   - Axis 261 (Globbing, THIS AXIS): node-glob +
#     minimatch
#   - + npm CLI (the package manager)
#   - + node-semver (canonical SemVer)
#   - + rimraf (canonical recursive-delete)
#   - + tap (test framework)
#
# Joining the multi-axis canonical-Node author
# cohort (now spanning ~9 distinct individuals):
#   - Sindre Sorhus (chalk + ~1000 microlibs)
#   - Matt Ranney + Redis Inc. (node-redis)
#   - Brian Carlson (node-postgres)
#   - Andrey Sitnik (PostCSS + browserslist + nanoid)
#   - Lovell Fuller (sharp)
#   - Paul Miller (noble umbrella)
#   - Devon Govett (foliojs umbrella + lightningcss)
#   - Matteo Collina (undici + pino + fastify)
#   - Isaac Z. Schlueter (npm CLI + node-glob +
#     rimraf + node-semver, THIS AXIS)
#
# node-glob's implementation strategy:
#   - Compile the glob pattern via minimatch (which
#     converts the glob to a JavaScript regex)
#   - Walk the filesystem using Node's stdlib `fs`
#     module's readdir/stat calls
#   - For each candidate path, test against the
#     compiled regex + decide whether to recurse
#     into subdirectories
#   - Callback-style API (older Node convention) +
#     newer Promise-based + async-iterator
#     variants in glob v8+
#
# Compared to alternatives:
#   - fast-glob: 2-3x faster on large file trees;
#     uses worker threads + improved I/O batching;
#     newer API
#   - tinyglobby: minimal alternative to globby +
#     fast-glob; smaller install footprint
#   - globby: Sorhus's higher-level wrapper around
#     fast-glob with extended features (multiple
#     patterns, gitignore-aware filtering)
#   - picomatch: just the pattern-matching engine,
#     no filesystem walk
#
# node-glob remains the canonical Node glob library
# despite faster alternatives because:
#   1. Stable API since 2011 (14+ years)
#   2. Universal compatibility (works in every Node
#      version + every JS runtime that implements
#      `fs`)
#   3. Direct dependency of npm itself (so it's
#      already installed wherever npm is)
#   4. Reverse-dependency network effect (changing
#      to a faster glob would require coordinated
#      changes across thousands of dependents)
#
# concat-glob-cli uses node-glob's classic callback
# API:
#   ```js
#   var glob = require('glob').glob;
#   var jsPattern = new glob(path, function(er, files) {
#     concat(files, dest, function(error) { ... });
#   });
#   ```
# Matched files get passed to the `concat` npm
# package's concatenate function which writes the
# combined output.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 261 :: Globbing libraries (shell-style file
#              pattern matching with `*` / `**` /
#              `[]` / `{}` syntax)
# Round 1483 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 261
#                                       (254th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : BurntSushi/globset           [R1481 _dropignore]
#             (RegexSet-backed batch
#              matching)
#   Go      : gobwas/glob                  [R1482 _panopticon]
#             (DFA pre-compilation)
#   TS/Node : isaacs/node-glob (`glob`)    [R1483 THIS FILE]
#             (Schlueter's canonical;
#              minimatch-based)
#
# isaacs/node-glob closes Axis 261 with the
# *foundational-via-reverse-dependency-network*
# pattern. The three lanes form a clean spectrum:
#
#   - Rust (globset): performance-tuned RegexSet
#     batch DFA; canonical via ripgrep ecosystem
#   - Go (gobwas/glob): performance-tuned per-pattern
#     DFA; canonical via MinIO/Traefik/Grafana
#   - Node (node-glob): older + slower than newer
#     alternatives BUT canonical via npm + the 14-
#     year reverse-dependency lock-in; can't be
#     displaced without ecosystem-wide migration
#
# Schlueter's foundational role in Node mirrors the
# Lemire (Roaring Bitmap at Axis 250) + Gallant
# (8-axis Rust footprint culminating in globset at
# Axis 261) patterns at the language-ecosystem-
# foundation tier.
#
# Cross-language interop at the pattern-grammar
# level - same glob pattern matches the same files
# across all three lanes, modulo minor extended-
# globbing edge cases (node-glob supports extglob
# `?(...)` / `*(...)` / `+(...)` / `@(...)` /
# `!(...)`; the Rust + Go canonicals don't).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - dropignore (Rust, globset): Dropbox sync-
#     ignore bulk applier
#   - panopticon (Go, gobwas/glob): file-watch
#     command runner
#   - concat-glob-cli (Node, node-glob): glob-aware
#     file concatenator
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (sync engine
# integration / file-watch automation / simple
# concatenation), three globbing implementation
# strategies (batch RegexSet DFA / per-pattern DFA /
# walk + minimatch), all converging on POSIX/GNU
# glob grammar.
#
# Axis 261 closes the round 1483 cycle - 254th axis
# closed total.
# ============================================================================

_concat-glob-cli() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-f --files)'{-f,--files}'[glob pattern of files to concatenate]:pattern:' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output file path]:file:_files' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_concat-glob-cli "$@"
